URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1314275924	2022-01-17 18:11:31.714043	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1				Unknown Sex, Adult (1)	United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Lincoln	US-ME-015		14			Pine Cliff Road	L17372468	P	43.8319060	-69.6508990	2022-01-08	08:55:00	obsr61305	S100400825	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	32			2	1	G7686131	1	1	1		Rushed over from the Western Avenue Bridge between West Boothbay Harbor and Southport, where the bird had been seen in the morning, once we heard the news that it had been spotted at Juniper Point. Reasoning that we’d have the best odds of spotting it looking north, we went searching for a public vantage point and found Pine Cliff Road. Our instincts turned out to be spot on, and we quickly found the bird on its prominent perch. Several other birders who had the same idea were gathered a little further up the road, leading to much rejoicing and several lovely reunions. Sunny and bright, but still quite breezy and chilly	Incredible record, long awaited chase opportunity after watching the saga develop for months. Finally tracked down after a sunrise sighting of the bird flying south reported from the boat launch between West Boothbay Harbor and Southport. Perched in a tall pine on Juniper Point, scoped looking north from Pine Cliff Road. Massive and imposing raptor, dark brown overall with brilliant white shoulder patches and tail. The immense golden bill was a striking field mark even at a distance. Constantly scanning the harbor, intensity of its glare was palpable whenever it looked our way. A goodly number of birders were able to observe it from this site until a group of observers approached on foot, walking through the intertidal zone right up to the base of its tree. At this point, it took off and headed across Boothbay Harbor, low over the water, coming to roost on the far eastern shore. We subsequently headed back over to the Maine State Aquarium to try our luck from that vantage point, details included in this checklist: https://ebird.org/checklist/S100401072

In brainstorming with the bois, it was determined we should divide our two teams near Thompson’s Gut to keep an eye out for the STSE as it leaves its morning roost. We opted for the Southpoint Bridge while RG and ZM posted up at Juniper Point. Using the recommendations from the Google Doc (posted below,) we arrived just before sunrise to be ready for the bird activity. The STSE was seen by ZM as it flew past him and toward us at 7:06am, where we saw it head NE and over the tree line and down to where it posed for crowds for a few hours: https://ebird.org/checklist/S100760506. Conditions were absolutely brutal despite a gorgeous sunrise: thermometer read 2 degrees F with a wind chill of -14 degrees F due to heavy, steady winds. ----STSE Google Doc. Primaries distinct, large and somewhat separated during flight  No antagonistic behavior observed during flight, but through personal communication with other observers, there was evidence of possible hunting of Canada Goose. In flight STSE came in over harbor from east (Fossetts Cove) flying at low altitude (approximately 15 feet above pier and dock associated with the Contented Sole building on north shore of Colonial Pemaquid State Historic Site;  43.879966, -69.521561) and proceeded west to tree and perched.  During perch, feathers around supraorbital ridge and head were fluffed. Head not extended but relaxed and neck feathers extended exhibiting warming behavior and actions.  Belly and flank feathers were extended over feet.  Individual appeared to be in relaxed mode and not agitated.  Some preening occurred before extension of body feathers.  STSE would periodically scan area below and outward from perch. Approximately at 16:14 STSE extended neck and was scanning area below perch, then at 16:21 STSE left perch and flew eastward, gathered elevation and turned back to west and flew over Thurston Point.  Anecdotally presumed to fly back toward the Boothbay Harbor area that it was seen previously.  STSE adult seemed to be in good health, non-agitated behavior, although prior to leaving perch seemed to be alerted to disturbance or possible prey.  American Crows were seen to mob the STSE adult while in the area before observed at perch (personal communication with other observers), and this possibly was the reason for movement outside of other perch sites in the area, although as stated earlier, some possible predation attempts were performed before my observations.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1319384730	2022-01-20 21:59:52.258041	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Lincoln	US-ME-015					Boothbay Harbor Yacht Club	L17437703	P	43.8475516	-69.6454013	2022-01-15	07:55:00	obsr108846	S100812337	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	234	0.274		3	1	G7720688	1	1	1		Brutally cold. Clear (visibility 10 miles); wind variable at 7 mph to NW at 10 mph, gusting to 22 mph; 1-7º F. Snow cover: the ground is mostly bare, except for scattered patches of ice. West Harbor Pond is completely frozen over, but the water below the bridge in Boothbay Harbor remains open.--We raced over to the Boothbay Harbor Yacht Club, stopped in their parking lot, and raced west across the road, where the sea eagle was quite obvious. A large crowd quickly assembled; unexpectedly, but not really surprisingly, Ann Mitchell was there too. For the first few minutes we were content to view from the initial location, but, realizing that a side view might be better (even if slightly more distant), we slipped down to the bridge across the mouth of West Harbor Pond. Only a few other observers were there when we arrived, but many others later joined us, some parking on the side of the road, or even on the bridge. Not surprisingly, this became an issue in short order, and after a couple of hours a few police arrived to try to keep both cars and observers in line. (It ws impressive to see, though, how quickly the crowds cleared after the eagle left.) We really wanted to see the bird in flight, but it persisted in giving us absolutely crippling views of it perched, for hour after hour; so periodically we'd take our chances and go sit in the car for a while to warm up, before heading back out for another stint for forced sea eagle viewing.--Note that this site is just north of the aquarium, across the harbor. We gather that Ross Gallardy and his party had a quick sighting of this bird early in the morning (from the Southport Swing Bridge?), which they did not post, but which sent them on a quest for the eagle. And after a thankfully short search, scanning all close coves and inlets, they came across the bird here. Congrats, and many thanks!--Saturday. Civil twilight begins 06:37, sunrise 07:09; sunset 16:26, civil twilight ends 16:58. Eastern Standard Time.--Mammals: none observed.	continuing mega rarity. extraordinarily cooperative, almost too much so. when we screamed into the parking lot here and got out of the car, it was perched in full sun in a tall pine on the west side of West Harbor Pond, across from the yacht club, and not 100 yards away. the massive eagle was facing us, which allowed for great view of the overall bulk, the massive orangey yellow bill, the beady yellow iris, the details of the shaggy brown head and breast plumage, and the white, graduated tail; but could see only a small piece of the white shoulders (and of only one shoulder to boot). after a while, then, we drifted down to the bridge below, where we could view it from more of an angle, and get a somewhat better appreciation of it. the eagle was quite aware of its surroundings, looking around constantly, but otherwise not doing much: it was big news if it do much as pulled one foot up and tucked it into the plumage. every hour or so it would act as if it might fly: pooping and wiggling the tail; or leaning forward and raising the tail (again pooping?), in each case leading to speculation that it was about to fly. and we all wanted it to fly, we wanted to see the majesty of those broad white shoulders and get a better sense of the overall heft of the bird. despite the apparent flight intention actions, and despite that fact that we were slowly dying in the brutal cold, however, the eagle stubbornly would not take flight. rarely if ever have I waited so long or suffered so much to see a rare bird in flight. after almost four hours, it finally did something dramatic, and turned around on its perch. this presented a possibility that we had not even counted upon: that it might take flight, but instead of flying right past or even over us, it might fly directly away. and that's about what it did: it soon took flight, heading away, and would have been lost behind the trees had it not angled off to the north and up a bit, so we had a decent view of it flight, albeit trending in the wrong direction. just at the end, it turned west again, and we lost it behind trees. as best that we can determine, it was not seen again for the rest of the day. many photos by Jay, Shawn (but none calendar worthy?), and many others.

Massive eagle with white shoulders, white tail, yellow-orange legs, massive yellow-orange bill. Gorgeous structure, with long, gently curved neck in flight. Bushy, widely spread tail in flight. First seen perched across the bay from Fort William Henry, mostly occluded, in a tall conifer. It eventually took off and flew north, landing in a large spruce. Next, it flew around the bay and disappeared in Fossetts Cove, where birders reported being able to see it from Pemaquid Seafood. After some time, it reappeared, taking off north up the channel, before returning in dramatic fashion to alight once again across from the fort. Finally, it briefly flew north over the treeline before flying southwest across the peninsula, towards South Bristol. Photos forthcoming.

Clear (visibility 10 miles); calm; 0º F. Snow cover: the ground is mostly bare, except for scattered patches of ice.--Word went out on the rare bird alert that the sea eagle was perched on Pooler Road, so we raced to figure out where in the heck Pooler Road was, and then how to get there. Of course, everyone one of the many eagle hunters in the area had the same inclination, so the road quickly became jammed with cars and birders. We pulled into the first quasi-close parking spot that we found, and then, following the crowd, rushed down the road to the site.--Sunday. Civil twilight begins 06:37, sunrise 07:08; sunset 16:28, civil twilight ends 16:59. Eastern Standard Time.--Mammals: none observed.	continuing mega rarity. perched in a pine at the end of Pooler Road. flew off shortly after we arrived, and almost immediately was lost from view. all of us had some kind of a view of it, although Jay, who got here first, probably saw more of it than Shawn or I did. for my part, my eye glasses were quite fogged from rushing along, and I didn't have the presence of mind to take them off in time: my only view of the eagle was through the fogged-over glasses, just as it took flight and then disappeared from sight. not a great end to my sea eagle experience, but given all that had come before, I had nothing to complain about.

Clear (visibility 10 miles); calm; -2º F. Snow cover: the ground is mostly bare, except for scattered patches of ice.--Despite not having seen the sea eagle fly north up Townsend Gut yesterday evening, we still suspected that it was roosting somewhere to the north, and so decided it was worth a check at dawn. And indeed it was! This morning there were many more observers than yesterday morning, although still perhaps only a dozen or so, and some of these were not quick enough to spot the sea eagle. In hindsight, we have to wonder if yesterday it hadn't flown up the Gut earlier than expected - perhaps even at noon? - which would account for the lack of sightings all afternoon, and the fact that we had missed it here at dusk last night.--Sunday. Civil twilight begins 06:37, sunrise 07:08; sunset 16:28, civil twilight ends 16:59. Eastern Standard Time.--Mammals: none observed.	continuing mega rarity. while my attention was focused on trying to relocate the female Hooded Merganser that we had seen here yesterday evening, we were alerted to the arrival of the sea eagle when someone watching from the east end of the bridge called out at ca 07:05 that it was coming. we snapped to attention, and had a terrific - if all too brief - view as it flew south, fairly low down, over the bridge and farther down the Gut. great views upstream from the bridge, when it was in better light; south of the bridge it was more backlit, and so became more of a silhouette. photographed by Jay, Shawn, and no doubt others.	
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1323767417	2022-01-22 11:06:19.347554	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Lincoln	US-ME-015					Pemaquid Harbor	L130929	H	43.8798599	-69.5206451	2022-01-21	15:00:00	obsr132390	S101165187	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	90			1	0		1	1	1		Very cold 15 degrees, sunny, and breezy. I was delighted to run into Doug Gochfeld, Michael and Louise, and Tom Johnson.	Third time's a charm!  I arrived at Colonial Pemaquid State Historic Site about 3pm and found that the bird had just been seen flying and then landed on a dock, I believe. I missed it. About 10 min later I was talking to a friend then walked over to a group of folks only to find that it just flew again and went left around the corner and further up the cove out of sight. I missed it again. Many people left. I stayed. About 20 min later I saw it come back around the corner from up the cove. I yelled to get the few remaining people on the bird. It then flew straight at us with the sun behind us and perfect lighting. Flying low it kept coming and flew passed us to the left. I snapped photos constantly as it approach, then my battery died! DIED! Darn! But I had a few shots that I hoped were good enough. The Eagle then landed across the cove and we set our scopes up and got all the newcomers on the bird before it flew again. It stayed for maybe 30 min, then pooped, stretched upward, and flew off along the tree tops to the right, then 180 turn and back to the left and over the trees and disappeared. What an amazing afternoon. In the crowd were folks from Maine, Texas, Oklahoma, Indiana, Alabama, New Jersey, New York, and I bet several more distant places.

Birding with Phil Magnant.-We decided to go to Spruce Point as there was a report on the GroupMe app that the STSE could be seen near the Burnt Island Light from Spruce Point. As soon as we arrived at Spruce Point we saw about a dozen birders looking at the STSE perched on a tall tree near the Burnt Island Lighthouse. We observed the STSE for a few minutes and then we saw it fly South to the point and then across the bay towards Squirrel Island. There the Eagle landed on a couple of spots along the shoreline and atop a few trees. We followed the bird for about an hour.	Seen perched near the Burnt Island Light and then flying and landing in Squirrel Island for about 45 minutes. Blurry photos taken.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1318948042	2022-02-12 22:44:13.242544	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Lincoln	US-ME-015					Boothbay Harbor Yacht Club	L17437703	P	43.8475516	-69.6454013	2022-01-15	07:55:00	obsr135617	S100772827	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	234	0.274		3	1	G7720688	1	1	1		Brutally cold. Clear (visibility 10 miles); wind variable at 7 mph to NW at 10 mph, gusting to 22 mph; 1-7º F. Snow cover: the ground is mostly bare, except for scattered patches of ice. West Harbor Pond is completely frozen over, but the water below the bridge in Boothbay Harbor remains open.--We raced over to the Boothbay Harbor Yacht Club, stopped in their parking lot, and ran west across the road, where the sea eagle was quite obvious. A large crowd quickly assembled; unexpectedly, but not really surprisingly, Ann Mitchell was there too (and apparently so was David Bates, although I did not know this at the time, and did not recognize him if I even saw him). For the first few minutes we were content to view from the initial location, but, realizing that a side view might be better (even if a bit more distant), we slipped down to the bridge across the mouth of West Harbor Pond. Only a few other observers were there when we arrived, but many others later joined us, some parking on the side of the road, or even on the bridge. Not surprisingly, this became a traffic issue in short order, and after a couple of hours a few police arrived to try to keep both cars and observers in line. (It was impressive to see, though, how quickly the crowds cleared after the eagle left.) We really wanted to see the bird in flight, but it persisted in giving us absolutely crippling views of it perched, for hour after hour; so periodically we'd take our chances and go sit in the car for a while to warm up (Jay did a good job of parking the car in spots with good visibility of the sea eagle), before heading back out for another stint for forced sea eagle viewing.--Note that this site is just north of the aquarium, across the harbor. We gather that Ross Gallardy and Zach Millen had a quick sighting of this bird early in the morning (from the Southport Swing Bridge?), which they did not post, but which sent them checking the nearby coves on a quest for the eagle. And after a thankfully short search, scanning all close coves and inlets, they came across the bird here. Congrats, and many thanks!--Saturday. Civil twilight begins 06:37, sunrise 07:09; sunset 16:26, civil twilight ends 16:58. Eastern Standard Time.--Mammals: none observed.	continuing mega rarity. extraordinarily cooperative, almost too much so. when we screamed into the parking lot here and got out of the car, it was perched in full sun in a tall pine on the west side of West Harbor Pond, across from the yacht club, and not 100 yards away. the hefty eagle was facing us, which allowed for great view of the overall bulk, the massive orangey yellow bill, the beady yellow iris, the details of the shaggy brown head and breast plumage, and the white, graduated tail; but we could see only a small piece of the white shoulders (and of only one shoulder to boot). after a while, then, we drifted down to the bridge below, where we could view it from more of an angle, and get a somewhat better appreciation of it. the eagle was quite aware of its surroundings, looking around constantly, but otherwise not doing much: it was big news if it did so much as pull one foot up and tuck it into the plumage. every hour or so it would act as if it might fly: pooping and wiggling the tail; or leaning forward and raising the tail (again pooping?), in each case leading to speculation that it was about to leave. and we all wanted it to fly, we wanted to see the majesty of those broad white shoulders and get a better sense of the overall heft of the bird. despite the apparent flight intention actions, and despite that fact that we were slowly dying in the brutal cold, however, the eagle stubbornly would not take flight. rarely if ever have I waited so long or suffered so much to see a rare bird fly away. after almost four hours, it finally did something dramatic, and turned around on its perch. this presented a possibility that we had not even counted upon: that it might take flight, but instead of flying right past or even over us, it might fly directly away. and that's about what it did: it soon took off, heading away, and would have been lost behind the trees almost immediately had it not angled off to the north and up a bit, so we had a decent, if brief, view of it flight, albeit trending in the wrong direction. just at the end, it turned west again, and we lost it behind trees. ('we' here refers only to Shawn and to me; Jay unfortunately missed this episode, as he had gone back to our Airbnb for an ill-timed bathroom break.) as best that we can determine, it was not seen again for the rest of the day. many photos by Jay, Shawn (but none calendar worthy?), and many others.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1314404853	2022-01-17 18:11:31.714043	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1				Unknown Sex, Adult (1)	United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Lincoln	US-ME-015		14			Pine Cliff Road	L17372468	P	43.8319060	-69.6508990	2022-01-08	08:55:00	obsr1083078	S100409305	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	32			2	1	G7686131	1	1	1		Rushed over from the Western Avenue Bridge between West Boothbay Harbor and Southport, where the bird had been seen in the morning, once we heard the news that it had been spotted at Juniper Point. Reasoning that we’d have the best odds of spotting it looking north, we went searching for a public vantage point and found Pine Cliff Road. Our instincts turned out to be spot on, and we quickly found the bird on its prominent perch. Several other birders who had the same idea were gathered a little further up the road, leading to much rejoicing and several lovely reunions. Sunny and bright, but still quite breezy and chilly	Incredible record, long awaited chase opportunity after watching the saga develop for months. Finally tracked down after a sunrise sighting of the bird flying south reported from the boat launch between West Boothbay Harbor and Southport. Perched in a tall pine on Juniper Point, scoped looking north from Pine Cliff Road. Massive and imposing raptor, dark brown overall with brilliant white shoulder patches and tail. The immense golden bill was a striking field mark even at a distance. Constantly scanning the harbor, intensity of its glare was palpable whenever it looked our way. A goodly number of birders were able to observe it from this site until a group of observers approached on foot, walking through the intertidal zone right up to the base of its tree. At this point, it took off and headed across Boothbay Harbor, low over the water, coming to roost on the far eastern shore. We subsequently headed back over to the Maine State Aquarium to try our luck from that vantage point, details included in this checklist: https://ebird.org/checklist/S100401072

A sizable crowd assembled to enjoy the show, including birders from near and far as well as plenty of curious locals. Clear blue skies and bright sun, still cold with light winds	Second encounter of the day with this incredible wandering individual, initial sighting details included in this checklist: https://ebird.org/checklist/S100400825 . After watching the eagle fly east across Boothbay Harbor from its perch on Juniper Point, we drove back to the Maine State Aquarium in the hopes of getting better views. The bird was soon refound perched high in a pine on the far shoreline, mostly obscured by the tree’s branches. The bold white wing markings and heavy golden beak helped pick it out at this distance. Eventually a pair of ravens began harassing it, appearing as small as crows in comparison to the hulking raptor. The eagle soon took off, initially flying west towards us but subsequently turning to head north along the treeline with the corvids in hot pursuit. A Bald Eagle soon joined the circling mob scene, allowing for another amazing direct size comparison with the Steller’s, who appeared a third as big again. Eventually the sea-eagle broke off from its pursuers and continued north, disappearing behind the trees. As far as I know, there were no confirmed reports for the rest of the day

Snow cover: the ground is mostly bare, except for scattered patches of ice.--Despite not having seen the sea eagle fly north up Townsend Gut yesterday evening, we still suspected that it was roosting somewhere to the north, and so decided it was worth a check at dawn. And indeed it was! This morning there were many more observers than yesterday morning, although still perhaps only a dozen or so, and some of these were not quick enough to spot the sea eagle. In hindsight, we have to wonder if yesterday it hadn't flown up the Gut earlier than expected - perhaps even at noon? - which would account for the lack of sightings all afternoon, and the fact that we had missed it here at dusk last night.--Sunday. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1319374558	2022-01-20 21:59:52.258041	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Lincoln	US-ME-015					Boothbay Harbor Yacht Club	L17437703	P	43.8475516	-69.6454013	2022-01-15	07:55:00	obsr16990	S100811676	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	234	0.274		3	1	G7720688	1	1	1		Brutally cold. Clear (visibility 10 miles); wind variable at 7 mph to NW at 10 mph, gusting to 22 mph; 2º-1 F. Snow cover: the ground is mostly bare, except for scattered patches of ice. West Harbor Pond is completely frozen over, but the water below the bridge in Boothbay Harbor remains open.--We raced over to the Boothbay Harbor Yacht Club, stopped in their parking lot, and raced west across the road, where the sea eagle was quite obvious. A large crowd quickly assembled; unexpectedly, but not really surprisingly, Ann Mitchell was there too. For the first few minutes we were content to view from the initial location, but, realizing that a side view might be better (even if slightly more distant), we slipped down to the bridge across the mouth of West Harbor Pond. Only a few other observers were there when we arrived, but many others later joined us, some parking on the side of the road, or even on the bridge. Not surprisingly, this became an issue in short order, and after a couple of hours a few police arrived to try to keep both cars and observers in line. (It ws impressive to see, though, how quickly the crowds cleared after the eagle left.) We really wanted to see the bird in flight, but it persisted in giving us absolutely crippling views of it perched, for hour after hour; so periodically we'd take our chances and go sit in the car for a while to warm up, before heading back out for another stint for forced sea eagle viewing. --Saturday. Civil twilight begins 06:37, sunrise 07:09; sunset 16:26, civil twilight ends 16:58. Eastern Standard Time.--Mammals: none observed.	continuing mega rarity. extraordinarily cooperative, almost too much so. when we screamed into the parking lot here and got out of the car, it was perched in full sun in a tall pine on the west side of West Harbor Pond, across from the yacht club, and not 100 yards away. the massive eagle was facing us, which allowed for great view of the overall bulk, the massive orangey yellow bill, the beady yellow iris, the details of the shaggy brown head and breast plumage, and the white, graduated tail; but could see only a small piece of the white shoulders (and of only one shoulder to boot). after a while, then, we drifted down to the bridge below, where we could view it from more of an angle, and get a somewhat better appreciation of it. the eagle was quite aware of its surroundings, looking around constantly, but otherwise not doing much: it was big news if it do much as pulled one foot up and tucked it into the plumage. every hour or so it would act as if it might fly: pooping and wiggling the tail; or leaning forward and raising the tail (again pooping?), in each case leading to speculation that it was about to fly. and we all wanted it to fly, we wanted to see the majesty of those broad white shoulders and get a better sense of the overall heft of the bird. despite the apparent flight intention actions, and despite that fact that we were slowly dying in the brutal cold, however, the eagle stubbornly would not take flight. rarely if ever have I waited so long or suffered so much to see a rare bird in flight. after almost four hours, it finally did something dramatic, and turned around on its perch. this presented a possibility that we had not even counted upon: that it might take flight, but instead of flying right past or even over us, it might fly directly away. and that's about what it did: it soon took flight, heading away, and would have been lost behind the trees had it not angled off to the north and up a bit, so we had a decent view of it flight, albeit trending in the wrong direction. just at the end, it turned west again, and we lost it behind trees. as best that we can determine, it was not seen again for the rest of the day. many photos by Jay, Shawn (but none calendar worthy?), and many others.

Arrived at approx 1:30 PM at Fort William Henry, Pemaquid Point, Maine; there were some 100 other birders already there.  The Steller's was perched about 1/4 mile away high in a hemlock, 10-12 ft from the top, near the shoreline across the bay inlet.  it was facing 45-60 degrees away from our viewpoint, but occasionally turned its head to observe us, giving us a look at its enormous beak. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1307135288	2021-12-31 23:59:54.687597	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023					Five Islands	L4294358	H	43.8238825	-69.7095300	2021-12-31	11:10:00	obsr121872	S99791678	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	90			1	1		1	1	1		Joined many other observers at stake out for Steller's Sea Eagle.	Super mega-rarity found late yesterday afternoon and alerted to Maine birding community by Nick Lund of Maine Audubon. Many observers on site this morning since daybreak.  I arrived just after 11 am. While walking down to dock along the road a yell rang out, "Flying Left". I watched this massive bird (larger than Bald Eagle) on deep wingbeats cross the skyline about 300 yards offshore, flying from one island to Crow Island. It perched momentarily high in an evergreen treetop where I got one photo before it departed perch apparently reacting to a Bald Eagle fly by.  Large dark bodied bird with obvious large white "shoulder patch" and huge yellow-orange beak. After 30 minutes or so the bird flew from the Crow Island area back across to the original island.  Minutes later it flew toward Mink Island where it apparently perched on the far side, out of sight of the crowd. One photo of bird on perch and one in flight.

Many people were there but  Peter Beckett from Bar Harbor came and got good looks in my spotting scope before flying south along the coastline off of Reid State Park.	Photos large yellow bill brown body and white shoulder patches.  We watched the bird fly south and out of the area over the ocean and across from Reid State Park. By the time I had arrived to Five Island pier the Steller's Sea Eagle had flown out to Mink Island and fortunately was sitting in a tall tree on the eastern side.  Marshall Iliff showed me my first view of this rare bird from Eurasia. I followed up with the best images I could get from this far away. It's large size is the first indication that  this is a large Sea Eagle. They are often referred to as the world’s most magnificent bird of prey, I watched as the bird flew to the small islands off of Reid State Park where it was later found. The large wings seemed to be followed by the outer primary feathers on the upward and downward strokes. The Steller’s sea-eagle is dark brown, impressive when compared to our native Bald Eagle and it is the largest of all sea-eagles.  It also is the heaviest known eagle. Its large size and ability to fly amazing distances. It is a beautiful Eagle to see. We also had comparisons in size to a Common Raven. There were a couple hundred people on and around the pier. For a moment in time, Georgetown was the epicenter of the Maine birding community, the center of the birding worlds gaze and amazement that his bird is here in Maine. I said about two weeks ago that this bird was coming to Maine. We have everything this bird needs to survive. Food and abundance of many pray options.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1307181128	2022-01-01 00:03:05.531697	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023					Five Islands	L4294358	H	43.8238825	-69.7095300	2021-12-31	12:06:00	obsr34603	S99795095	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	89	1.061		150	1		1	1	1		Amazing return visit with the sea-eagle, this time with Rosie Faunce joining me.	***mega; adult found yesterday after its stay in Massachusetts 12-20 Dec, and found yesterday in Georgetown, Maine. When Rosie Faunce and I arrived the bird had gone missing for the last 30 min but was apparently believed to be sitting behind Crow Island. We found Todd Day and chatted for just 2-3 min before a call went up that it was flying. I got a quick binoc look and then handed my bins off to Rosie, who was shorter than the crowd and could just see it in windows between heads. Since ID driven her all the way there, I immediately hoisted her up above the crowd height to see the bird and she got on it. Then we had to scurry around the wharf for a second view of it flying S past Malden and Hen Islands and then pulling up to land (obscured) on Mink Island—the southernmost in the Five Islands group. We tried to respot it from the lower wharf area for 10-15 minutes to no avail, connecting with Louis Bevier in the interim. ----While introducing Louis and Todd, some cries flew over the island and Todd noticed them swooping on something which we deduced would likely be the sea-eagle. We could see that whichever eagle it was, was perched just barely out of view so we grabbed the scope and walked up the road a bit, gaining elevation. I stopped at what felt like the right window for a different view and immediately saw it hunkered down low in a notch in the trees. It was not obvious, but the upper third of its body—including its huge bill—could be seen. We got a couple dozen people on it before it shifted perches. It took us a few minutes to realize, but that perch shift seemingly put it in full view from the wharf below, so we scurried back down and Todd quickly spotted it against the skyline of the island in full view. As had happened in Dighton, the bird was surprisingly hard for me to spot, takin a few seconds even in full view in a binocular. The sky was whitish gray behind the bird and I realized that it was because the huge white shoulder patch perfectly broke up the bird’s outline, making it seem like a craggy spruce tip more than the world’s largest eagle. Anyway, these views were excellent and prolonged: we left at 1:30 after 40 minutes of great perched views only to hear it flew S to Reid SB about 10 minutes later. ----Another amazing experience with this bird. Flight photos I have seen confirm the expected: this is the same bird seen in Massachusetts and Atlantic Canada, with the strongly notched p6 and white armpit spots being useful individual identifiers. To my knowledge everyone who wanted to see the bird today (and put in the time it deserved) should have been successful, a welcome change from its recent Massachusetts performance that rewarded only the first responders.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1306936108	2022-01-06 15:43:07.599893	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023					Five Islands	L4294358	H	43.8238825	-69.7095300	2021-12-31	11:20:00	obsr215193	S99775425	Traveling	P22	EBIRD_ME	100	4.023		1	1		1	1	1		Kayaking to get good views of Steller's Sea Eagle. Nice calm water 40 degrees air.	At the dock, the eagle started out at Malden Island at 11:15. We watched as the eagle flew across to Crow Island and called. Here eagles and crows harassed it and it eventually moved to the back center of the island. At this point I got in my kayak and paddled around the north end and saw the bird on the backside. Keeping off shore 40-50 yards the bird was generally not interested in me. I was able to watch the bird for 25 minutes until a pair of Gulls managed to push it from its perch. I followed its path toward Malden Island. I rediscovered the bird in the center of Mink Island with two Bald Eagles. Like the last spot, the bird sat on a high spruce perch and peered at passing birds and into the water. Wonder how much of its own food it gets vs. steals from gulls and Bald Eagles. I paddled back with it still there at 12:45. At about 1:15 after I had loaded up my kayak the bird flew away to the South out toward the tip of the peninsula as I gathered from the shouts and murmurs of the crowd. Ebird allows me to post 10 pictures, so I maxed out being this bird is so rare!

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1307596918	2022-01-10 12:43:48.702856	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023					Five Islands	L4294358	H	43.8238825	-69.7095300	2021-12-31	11:24:00	obsr49257	S99822396	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	134	0.653		150	1		1	1	1			America's Most Famous Eagle, present for (at least) its second day on the islands off the Five Islands pier. Upon arrival (at about 11:20) I quickly learned that the bird had last been seen retreating to the far side of Crow Island after showing well at various spots during much of the morning. The throng of birders who had gathered on the public pier numbered over 100, and behaved remarkably well. This is an active pier, with lobster boats offloading their catch, as well as pulling traps and loading them onto flatbed trailers. Not once did I hear any frustration among the lobstermen/women or the birders. I was joined by Marshall Iliff and his friend Rosie a few minutes after noon. A handy kayaker paddled to the far side of Crow Island, and not long thereafter, the Sea-Eagle was picked up in flight flying south toward Maiden and Hen Islands, not far off the end of our pier. with at least one nearby Bald Eagle. Initially mobbed by gulls, the two eagles flew in steady, powered flight toward Maiden and Hen, going between them. I moved to the western side of the lobster shack, ready to continue to scope the bird if it emerged. It popped back out at the south end of Hen Island, flying toward Mink Island. I tracked the bird in the scope to where I could no longer see it, but felt confident that I saw the flight change to perch somewhere, out of view. The Bald Eagle continue to fly past Mink Island, but the Sea-Eagle was not with it. Marshall and Rosie rejoined me, and Marshall was also confident that he had a good idea where the bird had perched. He examined the area in my scope, but was unable to find the bird. ----At this point, we were joined by Louis Brevier, my first in-person meeting. While talking, I started to notice crows mobbing a single spot near the skyline of Mink Island. At Marshall's suggestion, we started seeking higher ground, marking the spot on the island by a lone White Pine, and with a change of angle, Marshall was able to find the bird through a small window, perched on the far side of the island. About one-quarter or so of the bird was in view, with its massive, yellow bill showing well. We were able to set up two scopes on this line, and a few dozen folks were able to get this partial view. While watching, we saw the bird do a few perched flaps, and it eventually settled down slope of the island. We also noticed that the plucky kayaker was below this area, aiming a camera not far up. We all headed back down to the lobster shack, and started scoping the skyline again. We found the bird in good silhouette, with a wider window of view, and at this point anyone who was interested in seeing the bird could enjoy scope views for at least thirty minutes. ----This bird was difficult to detect against the skyline. The large white patch on the shoulder breaks up a typical silhouette of a raptor, making my raptor-seeking eye miss the bird. ----Large eagle, much more girth than nearby Bald Eagles. Immense yellow bill. Dark brown overall, with thin pale stripes on the head. Large white shoulder patches seen perched. These patches form a giant white leading edge of the interior two-thirds of the wing in flight. Large, white tail. Truly unmistakable. Nothing notably different about the flight style compared to Bald Eagles; perhaps a bit "heavier."

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1306953666	2022-01-04 14:28:12.152689	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023					Five Islands	L4294358	H	43.8238825	-69.7095300	2021-12-31	10:30:00	obsr539075	S99777411	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	180	0.100		1	1		1	1	1		I made the trek up the coast to try for the Steller's Sea Eagle that was reported yesterday evening around 4 PM. A dreary, foggy morning by sunrise with some chance of precipitation in the forecast later in the day; however, the weather on the day remained nice enough throughout the morning/early afternoon hours.	Photos.----Originally found and photographed by Linda Tharp on 30 December 2021. Likely the same bird that had appeared on the Taunton River in Massachusetts a couple weeks ago and has been appearing throughout North America (Alaska, Texas, Nova Scotia) over the past year.----Large eagle perched at top of conifer tree on island to the southeast of the wharf parking lot (appears to be Hen Island). Dark body with contrasting white shoulder patches visible while perched, Bird was initially facing away from the parking lot but periodically turned its head to reveal noticeably large orange bill. Immature Bald Eagle perched 20-30 m on adjacent tree top for comparison (Larger than BAEA). Bird took flight and headed north towards Crow Island, perched briefly on top of a visible confider perch, but then moved to the northeast side of the island, limiting visibility from the wharf parking lot. There was a brief vocalization from the Steller's as an adult Bald Eagle flew passed the same island at a relatively close distance followed by the Steller's moving to a different perch on the opposite side of the island. ----The bird remained in this position for 20-25 minutes before taking flight and flying southeast over the water before landing in the trees on one of the islands to the south of the wharf parking lot. The bird remained perch in the trees in this position approximately between 12:30 - 1:30 PM when I departed from the area.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1307875269	2022-01-01 22:45:01.238371	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023		14			Golf Cove	L17280730	P	43.8308295	-69.7102852	2021-12-31	08:30:00	obsr1456493	S99860963	Stationary	P21	EBIRD_ME	75			2	0	G7625968	1	1	1			Mega-rarity, incredible day all around. I got to Five Islands at around 7:45, a few dozen birders were milling about on the wharf and seawatching to see if they could spot the bird. Around half an hour later, someone yells, "We got it!" and take of running up the hill from the water. Everyone else grabbed their scopes and ran after him. When someone questioned him about where the bird was sighted from, he responded, "Just get in your car and drive". I got into the car with Nellie and checked my New England Birder's Discord and saw that someone had crossposted the coordinates from the listserv, so we drove about a mile north to the end of Moore's Turnpike. We joined the birders on the shore to see the eagle about half a mile out on Mac Mahan Island, right next to a house on the southern tip. It was incredible even from that far away, the white edge of the wings practically glowed in the morning sun. It eventually flew south to Turnip Island and I got my first good look at the bird through some very kind birders' scopes. The beak and head absurdly proportioned, it looks almost like a cartoon drawing of an eagle. The most striking thing was the eyes, the irises were a cool white. After a while the eagle flew from Turnip Island to the mainland and landed on a tree at the end of Blue Heron lane. The views weren't great, but luckily it decided to fly and land on the southern side of Golf Cove just a couple hundred feet away. Views from the docks were great, it was partially obscured by branches and only half in the sun, but it didn't really matter. Unfortunately, all birders were asked to leave by the property owners at around 9:45 as it was a liability issue. The eagle decided to head out at the same time as the birders, and it wouldn't be long before I got to see it again.

Refound this morning, first spotted at 8:14 by Matthew Gilbert as Reed and Chris were stumbling out of the car. Massive eagle with deep yellow bill, white scapulars, and white tail. Individual flew closer to Golf Cove as the checklist went on, perching proudly on spruce trees. Birders searching for this eagle should know that the entirety of Moore’s Turnpike is private, and the fishing co-op at the end of the road kindly asked our massive crowd to vacate the premises. The best public location to view this bird remains at Five Islands Wharf (43.8238114, -69.7093513). Many thanks to Linda Tharp, who first reported the bird yesterday, and Nick Lund and Maine Audubon for getting the word out. An amazing bird to end the year!

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1308032619	2022-02-03 14:42:03.432629	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023					Five Islands	L4294358	H	43.8238825	-69.7095300	2021-12-31	06:50:00	obsr53921	S99871186	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	420	2.400		1	1		1	1	1		My birding here was focused on the Steller's Sea-Eagle found here 29 December and reported yesterday afternoon. Over the course of the time here, there were probably 250 people, with up to 100-150 at times. Except for the earliest hour or so, I did not carefully record all individuals. Included here are birds encountered scanning the Sheepscot and residential lanes nearby. From 06:50 until about 08:30, I scanned from the end of the public wharf. I then walked to the end of Moore's Turnpike when we got word that the eagle was visible from there. I spent from about 08:45 until 10:30 at this site. I then returned to the public wharf via streets. I also walked to the end of Misty Lane twice, once alone. I was otherwise in the wharf area from 11:00 until 13:50, when I departed for Reid State Park. It was mild for this time of year, and relatively calm. The start was somewhat misty but that cleared before sunrise to partly cloudy skies, which became sunny for mid-morning. The tide was nearing high in the morning, then falling from about 08:30 onward. Temps mid 30s to 40s. [Track erroneous because I did not stop list or edit track]	Amazing luck that this wandering individual was found in Maine after last being seen 20 December along the Taunton River in se. Massachusetts. A local living near the Five Islands wharf had taken photos of the bird and reported this to Nick Lund's blog. Following up, we learned that she, Linda Tharp, had seen the bird on 29 December and then photographed it on 30 December.----A huge eagle that when seen with Bald Eagle appeared one third larger. The bill was especially deep and arched as well as being a rich orangish yellow (both cere and mandibles). Overall a slaty brown with broad white band across upper forewing (lesser and median coverts) and much more narrowly along forewing on underside reaching the wrist. The tail and upper tail coverts were white. The tail was wedge-shaped and sharply tapered to a point; the white on the upper tail coverts encroached on the lower rump (this was noticeable as the bird flew away and quite a distinct difference from Bald Eagle if the white on the wings could not be seen). Another prominent white area was the thighs, flanks, and under tail coverts. With my scope, I was able to see frosted light gray to whitish on the forehead and perhaps some of head. The eye was whitish and rather beady-looking in the big head. The large toes were yellow with black talons.----Characters linking this as the same individual in Massachusetts and before that in Canada were visible in photographs. On the right wing, there is a thin break in the webbing of the inner web on p6. On the right side near the axillars, there is a small white spot. The shape and ragged pattern of the rear border to the white forewing bar also show similar features to flight shots of the bird in Canada.----This morning, Matthew Gilbert and Reed Robinson (and ??) located the bird from a private property vantage north of the wharf (at the end Moore's Turnpike, N 43.83046 W 69.70974). The eagle was perched atop a conifer on the southeast corner of MacMahan Island (perch here N 43.83833 W 69.70564) that was 0.92 kilometers away (over 1/2 mile). With clear and sunny skies, the bird was easily identifiable. The eagle then flew to a perch on Turnip Island, only 0.45 km (a bit over 1/4 mile). We then watched the eagle fly out over the Sheepscot River and at one point seemingly attempt to grab a fish. It was almost as far out as the Bull Ledge buoy (green can) about 1 km away. This is a shallow ledge submerged at high tide, as it was at this time; so perhaps a good spot to find fish. This bird was easily identified at that distance. Gulls harassed the eagle, which eventually flew into trees at the end of Misty Lane and the other side of Gotts Cove (erroneously labeled "Golf Cove" on Google maps). At this point, the bird was 100 to 150 meters away but not easily seen in the trees where it perched. By 10:30, we were asked politely to leave the private property. Returning to the public wharf, we saw the eagle perch on Crow Island (at one point arching its neck and pointing its beak skyward as it called, a strange deep barking sound). We also saw the bird perch at the tops of trees on Malden Island and later Mink Island. At 13:40, the eagle flew south, more or less directly. I followed it as speck in the distance, and we assumed the bird might be off Reid State Park. No sooner had we concluded that when at 13:48 I got a text from Lance Benner that the bird had landed on the islands to the south off Griffith Head. It is possible that we could see the bird as it neared those ledges, which are 7 km (4.37 miles) from the wharf. For a good portion of this flight, I could still make out occasionally the white forewings on the upstroke and/or discern the point of white up the rump.	
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1306796067	2022-01-01 17:09:14.37673	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023					Five Islands	L4294358	H	43.8238825	-69.7095300	2021-12-31	10:06:00	obsr108577	S99762008	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	65			2	1	G7614918	1	1	1		The inevitable happened after so much publicity around this bird's appearance in Massachusetts last week: it was relocated at Five Islands! Thank god this was within striking distance from NYC! After the report came in the evening of the 30th, we knew we had to chase. We left NYC at 4am, arriving on site around 10. Remarkably warm, with light rain and fog the entire drive up, lifting to a low marine layer by the time we arrived, with temps in the high 30's and no wind. Huge numbers of birders, crowding pier while lobstermen we're at work!	Good thing so many people saw this bird, otherwise I wouldn't believe my eyes. Incredible. The stuff of legends. How does this species exist, let alone this individual make it's way to the northeast? massive bill, bulky chest and back, peaked head, bulging secondaries with exceedingly long primaries, and wedge shaped tail giving oscillating impression of power and awkwardness.----Initially relocated this morning from a private road near five islands boat landing, where evicted masses waited for it to emerge. It eventually did so after about 20 minutes of waiting, flying out of Golf Cove, out over Crow Island (flushing a seemingly miniature bald eagle en route), and landing on Malden Island where it sat regally for the next half hour or so, giving staggering views for all. It then flew over to Crow Island where it landed out of view. Liftoff from Malden towards crow especially dramatic, with the massive bird seeming to fly in slow motion through the still air and over still water, with a calling loon setting the soundtrack. We watched this from a rock outcrop exposed by low tide, away from the mob and making for a truly magical experience.

Note: this location is private property and we were asked to leave, so please don't go here.   Description from photos: large eagle.  Seen perched near a bald eagle for a direct size comparison and the Steller's was clearly larger.  Brown head; enormous bright yellow beak; extensive white on the leading edges of wings (top and bottom) that was conspicuous in flight and when perched.  White tail and white feathers on the legs.  Otherwise the body was brown.  Larger wingspan, slower wing beats, and longer body than the bald eagle seen harrassing it. URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1307009403	2021-12-31 23:59:54.687597	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023					Five Islands	L4294358	H	43.8238825	-69.7095300	2021-12-31	08:45:00	obsr313075	S99783303	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	75			1	1		1	1	1			Actually observed the bird at the end of Moore's Turnpike but then it was determined to be private property and all the birders had to leave. First spotted this incredibly majestic bird flying directly towards the large crowd of observers before it landed on the top of a pine in perfect sunlit lighting on Turnip Island to the north. Bird posed for pictures there for a while before it flew out over the bay, low and magnificently, where its enormous size was blatantly apparent. It occasionally slowed and hovered briefly over the water, suggesting hunting behavior? Then it flew south to a tree just south of Golf Cove (once again at the tip top, where it seems to like perching). Here it was harassed by a Bald Eagle until it flew directly towards the group of probably a hundred birders, landing in a pine along Golf Cove merely a hundred or so feet away, much to the oohs and ahhs of the crowd. ----At this point we were asked to leave the property, but as I understand it, it was later seen from the public Five Islands Wharf just to the south. Absolutely remarkable bird, in both size (that beak!!) and habits, and I couldn't think of a better way to finish out 2021, especially after the pain of missing the opportunity to chase it back in Massachusetts the week prior.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1306871539	2022-01-19 22:25:15.67574	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023					Five Islands	L4294358	H	43.8238825	-69.7095300	2021-12-31	08:45:00	obsr513087	S99770491	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	300			1	1		1	1	1		NOTE: This list includes our first stop at Moore's Turnpike where MG refound the bird. We were asked to leave (this is a private road) and relocated to Five Islands where the STSE turned up shortly after.----John Berry picked me up in Topsham and we drove down together. John departed part way through my stay at Five Islands.----A HUGE crowd of easily 200+ birds and photographers gathered on the wharf (with working lobsterman) and adjacent lawn/rocks. Practically everyone I know was here, between Five Islands and Moore's Turnpike: Doug Hitchcox, Louis Bevier, Noah Gibb, Turk Duddy, Nick Lund, Luke Seitz, Reed Robinson, Matthew Gilbert, Chris Sayers, Glenn and Anna Hodgkins, Doug Suitor, Jan Pierson, Ilsa and Ben Tucker, Gary Jarvis and Christine Murray, Tom and Jessy Foley, Laurie Pocher, Sean Hatch, Marian Zimmerman, Michael Boardman, Ethan and Ingrid Whitaker (mega congrats on the big year Ethan!!), Stan and Joan Deorsey, Susan Fenn, Charles Duncan and Laura Blutstein, and certainly others that I'm forgetting.----Cries of joy, laughter, and clapping accompanied each appearance of the eagle and many congratulations and slaps on the back were exchanged. The air was buzzing with excitement.----Absolutely epic bird and it's all the better that it's in my home county :-)	****MEGA****1st state record. The saga continues...----This bird was photographed yesterday afternoon by Linda Tharp near Five Islands and reported to Nick Lund, who put the word out. Matthew Gilbert refound the bird around 8:20-30 from Moore's Turnpike co-op (private property).----The bird eventually moved over to Five Islands where perhaps a couple hundred people viewed it. Between Moore's Turnpike and Five Islands, the bird moved to and from at least eight different perches while I was present, sitting in one spot for extended periods of time and occasionally disappearing on the back side of an island for a while. It took off just as I was leaving and flew south to Reid SP, where it was still being seen at the time of this writing (3:50 p.m.).----This was an absolutely enormous eagle, easily exceeding the size of the numerous Bald Eagles that were usually nearby and occasionally harassing the Steller's. --The MASSIVE bright yellow bill was very easily seen at most times and positively glowed in the sunlight. When perched, a large and conspicuous white slash was prominent on each wing and the bird had the appearance of wearing a pair of fluffy white "pants". The tail was white (perhaps a bit dingy) and the body plumage was a very dark brown with some golden streaking down the nape. A pale whitish eye was occasionally visible.----In flight the Steller's had a different profile than a Bald Eagle, looking bulkier but somehow also lankier with more planklike wings and a more protruding and sagging head and neck (no doubt this appearance was at least partially due to the massive bill, but the neck did appear longer and the head smaller in proportion to the body). The white in the wings appearing as a large slash when perched proved to be the marginal and maybe lesser(?) coverts and perhaps into the alula and primary coverts, covering the entire leading edge of the wing (except the primaries) with white on both the upper and lower surfaces, but being more extensive in the upper.----The bird called on one occasion upon alighting atop a conifer on Crow Island. It gave a series of repetitive, low barking notes with a somewhat hoarse sound to it, unlike the clear-toned calls that observers in Massachusetts recorded on 12-20-21.----[notes written from my memory of watching this bird through my scope]----Photos shortly

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1307342442	2022-01-01 12:32:32.972691	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023					Five Islands	L4294358	H	43.8238825	-69.7095300	2021-12-31	08:00:00	obsr105224	S99806568	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	90	1.609		1	1		1	1	1		Sea-eagle chase w/100+ birders present; walked from Lobster pound to Moore's Turnpike Rd; sun 37 degrees, nearly calm	Fortunately, the rarity has emigrated to Maine.  Located by another party just north of lobster pound.  M.ob. moved quickly to Moore's Turnpike (private), where bird was seen well perching on the tops of conifers on MacMahan and possibly Turnip Islands.  Nice views for 20 minutes before it flew to the south.  The white tail was visible when it flew and landed.  Very large eagle with a huge orangish-yellow bill and orangish-yellow feet.  White on wing coverts was extremely prominent ventrally and dorsally against the overall very dark plumage.  White on legs was also visible.  I was surprised that the white forehead illustrated in some guides was very difficult to see.  Grayish streaks on the fore neck were also visible.  Eye color was a shade darker than on a BAEG.  I was not overwhelmed by the bird's size so wonder if it is likely a male.  Although I had no direct comparison, it looked pretty close to the size of a large female BAEA.

Refound this morning, first spotted by Matthew Gilbert as Reed and Chris were stumbling out of the car. Massive eagle with deep yellow bill, white scapulars, and white tail. Individual flew closer to Golf Cove as the checklist went on, perching proudly on spruce trees. Birders searching for this eagle should know that the entirety of Moore’s Turnpike is private, and the fishing co-op at the end of the road kindly asked our massive crowd to vacate the premises. The best public location to view this bird remains at Five Islands Wharf (43.8238114, -69.7093513). Many thanks to Linda Tharp, who first reported the bird yesterday, and Nick Lund and Maine Audubon for getting the word out. An amazing bird to end the year!

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1308016042	2022-01-01 22:45:01.238371	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023		14			Golf Cove	L17280730	P	43.8308295	-69.7102852	2021-12-31	08:30:00	obsr2096184	S99874928	Stationary	P21	EBIRD_ME	75			2	0	G7625968	1	1	1			Mega-rarity, incredible day all around. I got Five Islands at around 7:45, a few dozen birders were milling about on the wharf and seawatching to see if they could spot the bird. Around half an hour later, someone yells, "We got it!" and take of running up the hill from the water. Everyone else grabbed their scopes and ran after him. When someone questioned him about where the bird was sighted from, he responded, "Just get in your car and drive". I got into the car with Nellie and checked my New England Birder's Discord and saw that someone had crossposted the coordinates from the listserv, so we drove about a mile north to the end of Moore's Turnpike. We joined the birders on the shore to see the eagle about half a mile out on Mac Mahan Island, right next to a house on the southern tip. It was incredible even from that far away, the white edge of the wings practically glowed in the morning sun. It eventually flew south to Turnip Island and I got my first good look at the bird through some very kind birders' scopes. The beak and head absurdly proportioned, it looks almost like a cartoon drawing of an eagle. The most striking thing was the eyes, the irises were a cool white. After a while the eagle flew from Turnip Island to the mainland and landed on a tree at the end of Blue Heron lane. The views weren't great, but luckily it decided to fly and land on the southern side of Golf Cove just a couple hundred feet away. Views from the docks were great, it was partially obscured by branches and only half in the sun, but it didn't really matter. Unfortunately, all birders were asked to leave by the property owners at around 9:45 as it was a liability issue. The eagle decided to head out at the same time as the birders, and it wouldn't be long before I got to see it again.

We were lucky enough to see it through a scope on the island to our left as we looked out to sea. Saw the dark body and large white wing patches. Got our best look when it flew from the island on the left to a longer island behind an island to our right (landing on the left side of a prominence on that distant island). Seen from Five Islands Lobster. Perched on top of tree on small island (approximately 43.826103, -69.705256). Large eagle with brown body and head, with distinct white shoulder patches. Many thanks to the other birders sharing scope views. ----I missed this closer to home, and had spent most of my holiday break checking the Mass Rare Bird Alerts thread, much to the annoyance of my wife. However, on the morning of the 31st, when I told her it was still being seen, she suggested I go. Many thanks to her for tolerating my day long-absence. I got a late start leaving Cambridge--a few minutes before 11AM. About 30 minutes into my drive I saw a message pop up that the eagle had flown, I considered the alternative of spending the day on Plum Island instead, but decided I would rather drive to Maine and miss the bird than cancel and miss the bird. With light traffic and only moderate speeding (which may have turned out to be crucial for the satisfying looks I got at Five Islands), I made it in a bit over 2.5 hours. I parked in one of the first spots I found about 0.2 miles down the road from the wharf, got my things together, and jogged down to the dock, arriving at about 1:30 PM. My timing was perfect, other birders graciously shared scope views. The bird flew at 1:38.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1308361028	2022-01-04 11:38:36.254004	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023					Five Islands	L4294358	H	43.8238825	-69.7095300	2022-01-01	06:44:00	obsr1749025	S99901521	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	220	0.519		2	1	G7630119	1	1	1			Continuing rarity. Spent the first two hours scoping from the end of the pier. The bird was spotted around 8:30 am on small island (to the left of Crow Island). It was only visible for a few minutes, from the far corner of the pier until it flew out of sight. Within a few minutes, the bird was spotted perching on a tree on Crow Island where it stayed for quiet some time, giving great views. The bird made its way gradually down the coast, stopping to perch on each of the small islands for varying amounts of time. The massive eagle appeared mostly black with bold white patches on the wings, white tail and “bloomers” and a comically large orange bill. Watching this bird fly through the fog and rain was a surreal experience. Couldn’t think of a better way to welcome in 2022 with this stunningly beautiful bird!

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1307569160	2022-01-01 17:34:12.745018	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023					Five Islands	L4294358	H	43.8238825	-69.7095300	2022-01-01	06:47:00	obsr489493	S99828750	Stationary	P21	EBIRD_ME	197			1	1		1	1	1			Arrived a little before 7 and spent the first 2ish hours scanning surrounding area from the end of the pier. Someone alerted the group that they had the bird in their scope, but it was distant and only visible from one vantage point on the pier. Not too longer after, the bird flew out of sight and the crowd started to work their way off the pier to give the working fishermen room. I walked up onto a rock on the edge of the parking lot and started scanning the islands again and quickly caught a flash of white at the top of a conifer on Crow Island: the Steller's Sea-Eagle! What a distinctive bird, hard to mistake it when compared to any other expected species in this area. In the lighting, the bird appeared mostly black with clean white patches on the wings, white "pants" and a ridiculously large orange bill. White tail seen in flight. The bird was absolutely stunning in flight. Awesome experience, despite the fog and rain.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1308141143	2022-01-01 22:45:14.775294	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023					Five Islands	L4294358	H	43.8238825	-69.7095300	2022-01-01	09:34:00	obsr1836778	S99886091	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	120			4	0		0	1	1			Drove up from Salem, Mass. with MD, NB, WA. Ran into BR at parking lot of Kennebunk Service Plaza……. Parked a two-minute walk up the road from Five Islands pier because we heard the town lot was filling up. As we rounded the bend and could finally see down and out toward the islands the bird flew from the left of the dock (north) heading to the right of the dock (south). Still approaching, I said to the group, “Is that the eagle??” And someone said “yes it is! Look now!” so I dropped my mittens and tripod and watched it land tail-down in a treetop on one of the southern islands through my binoculars. What a greeting!! All of us were absolutely stunned by this bird. It continued to hang about for awhile and eventually flew to the next small island, furthest to the right, where it displaced a BAEA and perched up again and was visible as just a white wing patch and yellow bill in the fog. We stayed until it flew out around the back of this small island, looping around the left side until it was out of view. We hung around until the rain really picked up. Photographers returning from the lobster boat reported it was still perched up on the back side of the small island as we were leaving. Came away with a variety of supremely mediocre cell phone photos through scope/nocs and with enormous smiles. What an extraordinary start to the new year. :)

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1310124109	2022-01-04 11:40:19.656732	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023		14			Grey Havens Inn, 96 Seguinland Rd	L17317043	P	43.8109951	-69.7209549	2022-01-02	14:30:00	obsr294200	S100057816	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	60			1	1		0	1	1			I arrived at Grey Havens Inn about one minute after the Steller’s Sea-Eagle departed!  I was told that the eagle had been perched near the top of the same tree on Wood Island for the previous 3 ½ hours.  Another birder told me that the Steller’s Sea-Eagle flew over my head chasing a Bald Eagle that had a fish. If I had only thought to look upward, I would have seen it!  That was the frustrating beginning to what was eventually a wonderful and exhilarating experience.  The one hundred or so birders that were at Grey Havens Inn gradually departed.  Several birders suggested that I remain at Grey Havens Inn, since their best guess is that the eagle could return to Wood Island since it had spent so much of the day there. For the first few minutes, I was alone looking for the eagle.  Then other birders gradually trickled in.  After about 30 minutes of waiting, one birder called out “I think I might see a Bald Eagle”. Disappointed, but hoping that perhaps the bird was not a Bald Eagle but a Steller’s Sea-Eagle, I quickly got my binoculars on the bird.  Extensive white shoulders, large white wedge-shaped tail, white leg feathers, with a fish in its massive orange bill.  I yelled out “it’s the Steller’s Sea-Eagle”.  An enormous relief followed by unbridled joy.  The Steller’s Sea-Eagle landed in the top of a tree on the mainland, perhaps 100 or 200m north of the tree at which it had spent the previous few hours before I arrived. The number of birders present continued to increase, perhaps reaching about 100 people, and each person quickly got onto the bird. It was wonderful to see so many happy, smiling birders.  The Steller’s Sea-Eagle remained atop the same tree, sometimes preening, looking around, appearing a little restless, as if it was about to leave. After about 30 minutes, the Steller’s Sea-Eagle left the tree flying to the northwest and then out of sight.  A truly amazing and incredible experience. Certainly, one of the most thrilling and memorable birds I have ever seen.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1308875571	2022-01-04 11:39:38.865055	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023		14			Grey Havens Inn	L17284721	P	43.8110800	-69.7208120	2022-01-02	08:55:00	obsr279837	S99950465	Stationary	P21	EBIRD	302			2	1	G7634049	0	1	1			Confusing mega!	
URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1308109324	2022-07-02 15:27:22.47316	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023		14			Grey Havens Inn	L17286403	P	43.8109420	-69.7204540	2022-01-01	14:18:00	obsr154922	S99883534	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	59	0.201		1	1		0	1	1			I mean, where do I begin? This bird is so unbelievable it deserves the full story. I knew about this bird’s North American wanderings for some time, but it seemed too distant or fleeting to pursue. But yesterday when I saw that it was continuing to hang out here, with wide open flights and cheap rental cars, I decided to make the trip. This morning I saw word that it had been refound in the same area as before, off Five Islands. I boarded my flight and hoped it would stick, hoping that the poor weather would keep it down. I arrived and booked it up 295. When I got to Five Islands the wharf was packed. At least 50 birders in line for the lobsterman’s boat trips to Mink Island, where the bird was apparently staked out, out of sight from land, and just as many lined up scoping the distant island. With not enough daylight left to wait in the line, I resigned myself to waiting for a distant look if the bird ever took off from its hiding place. As the boat set out again below us, the crowd noticed that it didn’t round the tip of the distant island like before, but instead hugged the shoreline. I began to realize that the bird had flown and somehow escaped our notice! Right then I got a text that there were good views from the inn, and sped over. When I arrived the eagle was perched in a spruce at the far southern end of Wood Island, across the harbor from the inn. Scope views revealed the massive orange-yellow bill, and chocolate brown color, and white tail. The bird remained perched for nearly an hour, occasionally moving a bit, and revealing white shoulder patches. I resolved to just stand in the rain and fog and wait for it to fly. It briefly vocalized twice—a raspy, gull-like call, not at all like its congener, Bald Eagle. After nearly an hour I was chatting with other birders when I heard a commotion, and looked up to see a huge bird flying toward us. At first I thought it was a heron. Then I got bins on it and realized it was the eagle! It flew past us at about 50 yards. It was an absolute behemoth. It flew effortlessly and boldly. Completely regal and a bird that is clearly used to being the ruler of its domain. As it flew it was harassed by crows. And just like that, it was gone. An unbelievable experience. Abysmal but diagnostic pics pending.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1308532445	2022-01-04 11:39:38.865055	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023		14			Grey Havens Inn	L17292145	P	43.8110530	-69.7208960	2022-01-02	08:37:00	obsr673869	S99917685	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	32	0.510		1	1		1	1	1		Stellers Sea Eagle chase attempt 2.  After failed attempt in Mass, I needed to make another attempt for this bird.  Left work on New Years day at 1030pm.  7 hours of driving and a caffeine pill later I arrived on no sleep (attempted to, but not successful).  We staked out the docks, but around 830am got the message the bird was being seen on nearby Wood Island.  Luckily was one of the prime spots for parking which made for an easy escape and was one of the first to arrive at the Grey Havens Inn (gracious owners were allowing birders to utilize their place for viewing).  Bird was perched atop trees a few hundred yards out into the river.  Shifted once to the opposite end of the island, eventually taking off North and across the channel.  With already so much time committed to this trip, I made the call to head home getting back at 430pm.  14 hours of driving, 2 hours of birding, and 1 spectacular bird!	Spectacular.  Re-found by other birders on Wood Island while the majority of us were at the docks.  Mad chase to get out and get to the spot.  Observed the bird for approximately 30 minutes before it took off across the river.  Believe it is estimated that approximately 4000 birds remain, most on the kamchatka peninsula in Russia.  Size was deceiving until the bird took flight, and when it did, man was it impressive.  Bird averages about 50% heavier than our Bald Eagle which was very evident during flight with an almost pot belly appearance.  Striking white markings with a very large, bright yellow beak.  This was a memorable chase that I will not soon forget.

Epic looks from the Town lobster docks!  Perched prominently, and quite regally, on Crow, Malden, Hen, and Mink Islands.  Eventually disappearing behind Mink, but not before our group viewed the bird for well over an hour.  Truly amazing looks, especially while in flight.  A MOB'd, and well documented, bird first reported to the Maine-Birds (Google) Group by Linda Tharp via Nick Lund on the 30th.  This chocolatey brown bird with its massively exaggerated hooked orange bill, large white "shoulders," and long (almost Booby-like) white wedge-shaped tail has been burned indelibly into the mind.

URN:CornellLabOfOrnithology:EBIRD:OBS1308285027	2022-01-04 11:38:36.254004	7973	species	avibase-C481FB24	Steller's Sea-Eagle	Haliaeetus pelagicus				1					United States	US	Maine	US-ME	Sagadahoc	US-ME-023					Five Islands	L4294358	H	43.8238825	-69.7095300	2022-01-01	06:44:00	obsr610776	S99896239	Traveling	P22	EBIRD	220	0.519		2	1	G7630119	1	1	1			Continuing rarity. Spent roughly first two hours scoping from the end of the pier. The bird was spotted around 8:30/9 am on small island (to the left of Crow Island). It was only visible for a few minutes, from the far corner of the pier until it flew out of sight. Within a few minutes, the bird was spotted perching on a tree on Crow Island where it stayed for quiet some time, giving great views. The bird made its way gradually down the coast, stopping to perch on each of the small islands for varying amounts of time. The massive eagle appeared mostly black with bold white patches on the wings, white tail and “bloomers” and a comically large orange bill. Watching this bird fly through the fog and rain was a surreal experience. Couldn’t think of a better way to welcome in 2022 with this stunningly beautiful bird!

Enormous and very distinctive black and white raptor with white wing patches, white wedge-shaped tail, and comically large orange-yellow bill.
